# Prefer HTML5 Over JavaScript

## Principle

**Use native HTML5 features and semantic elements instead of JavaScript implementations** whenever possible. This improves performance, accessibility, and maintainability.

## Rationale

- **Performance**: Native browser features are faster than JS implementations
- **Accessibility**: HTML5 semantic elements have built-in ARIA support
- **Progressive Enhancement**: Works without JavaScript enabled
- **Maintainability**: Less code to maintain, fewer bugs
- **SEO**: Search engines better understand semantic HTML
- **Mobile**: Better touch support and native mobile features

## Guidelines

### Forms & Input

#### ❌ BAD - JavaScript validation
```html
<input type="text" id="email">
<script>
  document.getElementById('email').addEventListener('blur', function() {
    if (!this.value.includes('@')) {
      alert('Invalid email');
    }
  });
</script>
```

#### ✅ GOOD - HTML5 native validation
```html
<input type="email" name="email" required pattern="[a-z0-9._%+-]+@[a-z0-9.-]+\.[a-z]{2,}$">
```

### Navigation & Links

#### ❌ BAD - JavaScript navigation
```html
<div onclick="window.location='/page'">Go to page</div>
```

#### ✅ GOOD - Native anchor tag
```html
<a href="/page">Go to page</a>
```

### Modals & Dialogs

#### ❌ BAD - Custom JavaScript modal
```html
<div class="modal" id="myModal">...</div>
<script>
  function openModal() {
    document.getElementById('myModal').style.display = 'block';
  }
</script>
```

#### ✅ GOOD - HTML5 `<dialog>` element
```html
<dialog id="myModal">
  <p>Modal content</p>
  <form method="dialog">
    <button>Close</button>
  </form>
</dialog>
<script>
  document.getElementById('myModal').showModal();
</script>
```

### Details & Accordions

#### ❌ BAD - JavaScript accordion
```html
<div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion()">Header</div>
<div class="accordion-content" id="content">Content</div>
```

#### ✅ GOOD - HTML5 `<details>` element
```html
<details>
  <summary>Header</summary>
  <p>Content</p>
</details>
```

### Images & Media

#### ❌ BAD - JavaScript lazy loading
```html
<img data-src="image.jpg" class="lazy">
<script>
  // Lazy loading implementation
</script>
```

#### ✅ GOOD - Native lazy loading
```html
<img src="image.jpg" loading="lazy" alt="Description">
```

### Video & Audio

#### ❌ BAD - Custom video controls
```html
<video id="video">
<script>
  // Custom play/pause controls
</script>
```

#### ✅ GOOD - Native video controls
```html
<video controls>
  <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>
```

### Form Elements

#### Use native HTML5 input types:
- `type="email"` - Email validation
- `type="url"` - URL validation
- `type="tel"` - Phone number
- `type="date"` - Date picker
- `type="time"` - Time picker
- `type="number"` - Number input with spinner
- `type="range"` - Slider
- `type="color"` - Color picker
- `type="search"` - Search input
- `type="month"`, `type="week"` - Date ranges

#### Form attributes:
- `required` - Required field validation
- `pattern` - Regex validation
- `min`, `max` - Range validation
- `step` - Increment values
- `autocomplete` - Browser autocomplete
- `placeholder` - Hint text

### Semantic HTML5 Elements

Use semantic elements instead of generic divs:

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD -->
<div class="header">...</div>
<div class="nav">...</div>
<div class="main">...</div>
<div class="footer">...</div>

<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<header>...</header>
<nav>...</nav>
<main>...</main>
<footer>...</footer>
```

Other semantic elements:
- `<article>` - Independent content
- `<section>` - Thematic grouping
- `<aside>` - Sidebar content
- `<figure>` + `<figcaption>` - Images with captions
- `<time>` - Dates and times
- `<mark>` - Highlighted text
- `<progress>` - Progress bars
- `<meter>` - Gauge/measurement

### When JavaScript is Still Needed

JavaScript is appropriate for:
- Complex interactions (drag & drop, complex animations)
- Dynamic content loading (AJAX)
- Real-time updates
- Client-side routing (SPAs)
- Complex state management
- Features not available in HTML5

But always:
1. **Start with HTML5** - Use native features first
2. **Enhance with JS** - Add JavaScript only when needed
3. **Progressive Enhancement** - Ensure core functionality works without JS

## Examples for This Project

### Lightbox
- Current: Custom vanilla JS lightbox ✅ (Good - no native alternative)
- Could use: `<dialog>` for simple modals

### Forms
- Use `type="email"`, `required`, `pattern` attributes
- Native validation instead of JS validation

### Navigation
- Use `<nav>` semantic element
- Native anchor tags, not `onclick` handlers

### Images
- Use `loading="lazy"` attribute
- Use `<picture>` for responsive images
- Use `<figure>` for images with captions

## Checklist

When implementing a feature:
- [ ] Is there an HTML5 native alternative?
- [ ] Can I use semantic HTML5 elements?
- [ ] Can I use native form validation?
- [ ] Can I use native lazy loading?
- [ ] Can I use native media controls?
- [ ] Does it work without JavaScript?
- [ ] Is it accessible by default?
